        body: "For professionals who are considering a career change into interior design, the three IDI graduates profiled in this article offer practical advice drawn from their own experience. Michael Chen recommends starting with a self-assessment: do you love the idea of interior design, or do you love the reality of it? Before committing to a program, he suggests spending time with working designers to understand what the day-to-day work actually involves. Shadow a designer on a job site. Attend an industry event. Visit a design school campus and talk to current students. If the reality excites you as much as the idea, the investment is worth making. Andrea Morales emphasizes the importance of financial planning. A career change involves a period of reduced income, and the stress of financial uncertainty can undermine the learning experience if it is not managed proactively. She recommends building a financial cushion before enrolling, exploring scholarship and financial aid options, and choosing a program structure that allows for part-time work during the study period. IDI's program offerings, which range from the focused Certificate to the comprehensive BA and MIA, provide flexibility that accommodates different life circumstances. James Whitfield advises career changers to embrace their previous experience rather than trying to leave it behind. The skills, knowledge, and perspectives you have developed in your first career are not irrelevant to design — they are assets that will differentiate you in the marketplace. A designer who understands healthcare, or education, or finance, or technology brings a depth of sector-specific knowledge that clients and employers value. IDI's faculty are skilled at helping students identify and leverage these transferable competencies. All three graduates agree on one final point: the nervousness you feel before making the leap does not go away until you actually jump. The decision to change careers is rarely comfortable, but the regret of not trying, they say, is far worse than the discomfort of starting something new."
